comment: I feel like I'm repeating myself but fixing London's ailing IPO market requires genuine reform, they've clearly lost its ability to function as a place for firms to raise capital. author: @ccsas5398
comment:
As a North Londoner, watching the slow unravelling of the City's standing is deeply unsettling. We're losing our edge, and clients are fleeing to New York for a reason.

There's a very British optimism that surfaces at times like this—a talent for talking big about a "calm, orderly" recovery. But to me, it feels more like pride before the fall. I just can't see us gracefully escaping this spiral.

Frankly, I've come to believe it will take a once-in-a-generation seismic shock—a market crash or worse—to force the kind of radical, collective change we need. It's a terrifying thought, and I'm scared for what the future holds for our financial heart.

Also from North London, we gave up our position as the banking hub for EUR trade. We told the world to go away,  we were once the place to do EUR business, but we surrendered that.
